\begin_layout Section
Delegation Architecture
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:delegation_architectire}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In current implementation delegation is achieved through Identity Delegation
 implemented using X509 Proxy Certificates as defined in RFC 3820.
 Client wishing to allow service to act on it's behalf provides Proxy Certificat
e to the service using Web Service based Delegation interface described
 in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:delegation_interface}

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For limitinng the scope of delegated credentials along with usually used
 time constraints it is possible to attach Policy document to Proxy Certificate.
 According to RFC 3820 Policy is stored in 
\emph on
ProxyPolicy
\emph default
 extension.
 In order not to introduce new type of object Policy is assigned 
\emph on
id-ppl-anyLanguage
\emph default
 identifier.
 RFC 3820 allows any octet string associated with such object.
 We are using textual representation of ARC Policy XML document.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each deployment implementing Delegation Restrictions must use dedicated
 Security Handler plugin (see section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:delegation_collector}

\end_inset

) to collect all Policy documents from Proxy Certificates used for establishing
 secure connection.
 Then those documents must be processed by dedicated Policy Decision Point
 plugin (see section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:delegation_pdp}

\end_inset

) to make a final decision based on collected Policies and various information
 about client's identity and requested operation.
 Service or MCC chain supporting Delegation Restrictions must accept negative
 decision of this PDP as final and do not override it with any other decision
 based on other policies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Delegation Collector
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:delegation_collector}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This Security Attribute is collected by dedicated Security Handler plugin
 named 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
delegation.pdp
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 avaialble in 
\emph on
arcpdc
\emph default
 plugins' library.
 It extracts policy document stored inside X509 certificate proxy extension
 as defined in RFC3820 and described in Section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:delegation_architectire}

\end_inset

.
 All proxy certificates in a chain provided by client are examined and all
 available policies are extracted.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extracted content is converted into XML document.
 Then document is checked to be of Arc Policy kind.
 If policy is not recognized as Arc Policy procedure fails and that causes
 failure of comunication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proxy certificates with 
\emph on
id-ppl-inheritAll
\emph default
 property are passed through and no policy document is generated for them.
 Proxies with other type of policies including 
\emph on
id-ppl-independent
\emph default
 are not accepted and generate immediate failure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Delegation PDP
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:delegation_pdp}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DelegationPDP is similar to ArcPDP described above except that it takes
 it's Policy documents directly from Security Attributes.
 Differently from Arc PDP it is meant to be used for enforcing policies
 defined by client.
\end_layout

