\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:delegation_interface}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Web Service delegation interface.
 Each ARC1 service wishing to accept delegated credentials implements this
 interface.
 Here is how delegation procedure works:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 1
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Client contacts service requesting operation DelegateCredentialsInit.
 This operation has no arguments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Service responds with 
\emph on
DelegateCredentialsInitResponse
\emph default
 message with element 
\emph on
TokenRequest
\emph default
.
 That element contains credentials request generated by service in 
\emph on
Value
\emph default
.
 Type of request is defined by attribute 
\emph on
Format
\emph default
.
 Currently only supported format is 
\emph on
x509
\emph default
.
 Along with 
\emph on
Value
\emph default
 service provides identifier 
\emph on
Id
\emph default
 which is used in second step.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Step 2
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Client requests 
\emph on
UpdateCredentials
\emph default
 operation with 
\emph on
DelegatedToken
\emph default
 argument.
 This element contains 
\emph on
Value
\emph default
 with serialized delegated credentials and 
\emph on
Id
\emph default
 which links it to first step.
 Delegated token element may also contain multiple 
\emph on
Reference
\emph default
 elements.
 
\emph on
Reference
\emph default
 refers to the object which these credentials should be applied to in a
 way specific to the service.
 
\newline
The 
\emph on
DelegatedToken
\emph default
 element must also be used for delegating credentials when Step 2 is combined
 with other operations on service.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Service responds with empty 
\emph on
UpdateCredentialsResponse
\emph default
 message.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
